0d7ee6><circle cx="46" cy="46" r="45.5" stroke="#FFFFFF" class="pulsing" transform-origin="46 46" data-v-c40d7ee6></circle><circle cx="46" cy="46" r="7" fill="#FFFFFF" data-v-c40d7ee6></circle><path d="M46 47.5L272.5 65" stroke="#FFFFFF" data-v-c40d7ee6></path></svg><div class="scene__info" data-v-c40d7ee6><p class="scene__info-title" data-v-c40d7ee6>Haemorrhoids</p><p class="scene__info-text" data-v-c40d7ee6> Enlarged and swollen veins in and around the anus or lower rectum.<sup data-v-c40d7ee6>1</sup></p><button class="scene__info-button" data-v-c40d7ee6> Learn more </button></div></div></div><p class="scene__refferences p5" data-v-c40d7ee6> REFERENCE: 1. Haemorrhoids. HealthDirect. Available at: <a href="https://www.healthdirect.gov.au/haemorrhoids-piles" target="_blank" class="p5-italic" data-v-c40d7ee6>https://www.healthdirect.gov.au/haemorrhoids-piles</a> . Accessed: June 2023. </p></div><div class="scene scene-3" data-v-c40d7ee6><div class="scene__item" data-v-c40d7ee6><div class="scene__text" data-v-c40d7ee6><svg width="379" height="92" viewBox="0 0 379 92" fill="none" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" data-v-c40d7ee6><circle cx="333" cy="46" r="45.5" stroke="#FFFFFF" class="pulsing" transform-origin="333 46" data-v-c40d7ee6></circle><circle cx="333" cy="46" r="7" fill="#FFFFFF" data-v-c40d7ee6></circle><path d="M1 18L339.5 46.5" stroke="#FFFFFF" data-v-c40d7ee6></path></svg><div class="scene__info" data-v-c40d7ee6><p class="scene__info-title" data-v-c40d7ee6>Anal fissures</p><p class="scene__info-text" data-v-c40d7ee6> Small tears in the skin that lines the anus and are often caused by passing hard stool.<sup data-v-c40d7ee6>1</sup></p><button class="scene__info-button" data-v-c40d7ee6> Learn more </button></div></div></div><p class="scene__refferences p5" data-v-c40d7ee6> REFERENCE: 1. Anal fissure. HealthDirect. Available at: <a href="https://www.healthdirect.gov.au/anal-fissure" target="_blank" class="p5-italic" data-v-c40d7ee6>https://www.healthdirect.gov.au/anal-fissure</a> Accessed: June 2023. </p></div></div><div class="scenes-mobile" data-v-c40d7ee6><div class="scene-mobile scene-mobile-1" data-v-c40d7ee6><!--[--><button class="mobile-point" data-v-c40d7ee6><div class="mobile-point__inner" data-v-c40d7ee6></div></button><button class="mobile-point" data-v-c40d7ee6><div class="mobile-point__inner" data-v-c40d7ee6></div></button><button class="mobile-point" data-v-c40d7ee6><div class="mobile-point__inner" data-v-c40d7ee6></div></button><button class="mobile-point" data-v-c40d7ee6><div class="mobile-point__inner" data-v-c40d7ee6></div></button><button class="mobile-point" data-v-c40d7ee6><div class="mobile-point__inner" data-v-c40d7ee6></div></button><button class="mobile-point" data-v-c40d7ee6><div class="mobile-point__inner" data-v-c40d7ee6></div></button><button class="mobile-point" data-v-c40d7ee6><div class="mobile-point__inner" data-v-c40d7ee6></div></button><!--]--></div><div class="scene-mobile scene-mobile-2" data-v-c40d7ee6><button class="mobile-point" data-v-c40d7ee6><div class="mobile-point__inner" data-v-c40d7ee6></div></button></div><div class="scene-mobile scene-mobile-3" data-v-c40d7ee6><button class="mobile-point" data-v-c40d7ee6><div class="mobile-point__inner" data-v-c40d7ee6></div></button></div></div><!----><div class="scoll-down-indicator" data-v-c40d7ee6><span data-v-c40d7ee6> Scroll to Discover </span><svg width="40" height="40" viewbox="0 0 32 32" fill="none" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" data-v-c40d7ee6><g opacity="0.7"><path d="M4 16C4 22.6274 9.37258 28 16 28C22.6274 28 28 22.6274 28 16C28 9.37258 22.6274 4 16 4C9.37258 4 4 9.37258 4 16Z" stroke="#11274C" stroke-width="1" stroke-miterlimit="10"></path><g><animateTransform attributeName="transform" attributeType="XML" type="translate" values="0 0; 0 2; 0 -2; 0 0" dur="2s" repeatCount="indefinite"></animateTransform><path d="M11.7569 16.7573L15.9996 20.9999L20.2422 16.7573" stroke="#11274C" stroke-width="1" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"></path><path d="M16 11L16 21" stroke="#11274C" stroke-width="1" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"></path></g></g></svg></div></div></div><div class="page__html" data-v-5588cc5e><section id="differences" class="page__table-section" data-v-5588cc5e><div class="table-section" data-v-5588cc5e data-v-b9302117><div class="table-wrapper" data-v-b9302117><table class="table" data-v-b9302117><thead class="table__thead" data-v-b9302117><tr data-v-b9302117><th class="h1 js-fade" data-v-b9302117> Anal fissures<span data-v-b9302117><sup data-v-b9302117>1</sup></span></th><th class="h1 js-fade" data-v-b9302117>vs</th><th class="h1 js-fade" data-v-b9302117> Haemorrhoids<span data-v-b9302117><sup data-v-b9302117>2</sup></span></th></tr></thead><tbody class="table__tbody" data-v-b9302117><tr data-v-b9302117><td class="white-td js-fade" data-v-b9302117> Small tears in the skin that lines the anus. </td><td class="blue-td js-fade" data-v-b9302117>Definitions</td><td class="white-td js-fade" data-v-b9302117> Swollen veins that occur in and around the anus. </td></tr><tr data-v-b9302117><td class="white-td js-fade" data-v-b9302117> Usually caused by injury to the area. This can happen when passing a large or hard stool. </td><td class="blue-td js-fade" data-v-b9302117>Causes</td><td class="white-td js-fade" data-v-b9302117> Usually caused by constipation and straining to pass stools. </td></tr><tr data-v-b9302117><td class="white-td js-fade" data-v-b9302117><ul data-v-b9302117><li data-v-b9302117><span class="list-circle" data-v-b9302117></span>Pain during and after going to the toilet </li><li data-v-b9302117><span class="list-circle" data-v-b9302117></span>Cramping around the anus</li><li data-v-b9302117><span class="list-circle" data-v-b9302117></span>Blood on toilet paper or stool </li><li data-v-b9302117><span class="list-circle" data-v-b9302117></span>Itchiness around the anus</li></ul></td><td class="blue-td js-fade" data-v-b9302117>Symptoms</td><td class="white-td js-fade" data-v-b9302117><ul data-v-b9302117><li data-v-b9302117><span class="list-circle" data-v-b9302117></span>Bright red blood on the toilet paper or in the toilet </li><li data-v-b9302117><span class="list-circle" data-v-b9302117></span>Itchiness, discomfort, or pain around the anus </li><li data-v-b9302117><span class="list-circle" data-v-b9302117></span>Lump that protrudes out of the anus </li></ul></td></tr><tr data-v-b9302117><td class="white-td js-fade" data-v-b9302117><ul data-v-b9302117><li data-v-b9302117><span class="list-circle" data-v-b9302117></span> Muscle relaxant cream (such as 0.2% glyceryl trinitrate) </li><li data-v-b9302117><span class="list-circle" data-v-b9302117></span> Pain-relieving medication</li><li data-v-b9302117><span class="list-circle" data-v-b9302117></span>Botox injections</li><li data-v-b9302117><span class="list-circle" data-v-b9302117></span>Some may require surgery (sphincterotomy) </li></ul></td><td class="blue-td js-fade" data-v-b9302117>Treatment</td><td class="white-td js-fade" data-v-b9302117><ul data-v-b9302117><li data-v-b9302117><span class="list-circle" data-v-b9302117></span>Over-the-counter haemorrhoid treatments </li><li data-v-b9302117><span class="list-circle" data-v-b9302117></span>Injection (sclerotherapy)</li><li data-v-b9302117><span class="list-circle" data-v-b9302117></span>Rubber band ligation</li><li data-v-b9302117><span class="list-circle" data-v-b9302117></span>Some may require surgery (haemorrhoidectomy) </li></ul></td></tr></tbody></table></div><div class="table__addition" data-v-b9302117><p class="table__addition_first b1 js-fade" data-v-b9302117> The key difference between anal fissures and haemorrhoids is the location where the problem occurs in the rectum. Anal fissures are small external tears in the skin that lines the anus. In comparison, haemorrhoids are enlarged and swollen veins present inside the rectum, or under the skin surrounding the anus.<sup data-v-b9302117>1,2</sup></p><div class="table__addition_second js-fade" data-v-b9302117><div class="addition-title" data-v-b9302117><a href="<?php echo get_stylesheet_directory_uri(); ?>/documents/comparison.pdf" target="_blank" class="button" data-v-b9302117 data-v-8cc40661>PRINT PDF</a></div><p class="addition-references js-fade p5" data-v-b9302117> REFERENCES: 1. Anal fissure. HealthDirect. Available at: <a href="https://www.healthdirect.gov.au/anal-fissure" target="_blank" class="p5-italic" data-v-b9302117>https://www.healthdirect.gov.au/anal-fissure</a> Accessed: June 2023. 2. Haemorrhoids. HealthDirect. Available at: <a href="https://www.healthdirect.gov.au/haemorrhoids-piles" target="_blank" class="p5-italic" data-v-b9302117>https://www.healthdirect.gov.au/haemorrhoids-piles</a>. Accessed: June 2023. </p></div></div></div></section><section id="rectogesic" class="page__diagnose-section" data-v-5588cc5e><div class="diagnose" data-v-5588cc5e data-v-68c73f99><div class="diagnose__block" data-v-68c73f99><div class="diagnose__col" data-v-68c73f99><p class="diagnose__title h1 js-fade" data-v-68c73f99> Reached an anal fissure diagnosis? </p><p class="diagnose__subtitle h2 js-fade" data-v-68c73f99> It is time to recommend Rectogesic® as a treatment option. </p></div><div class="diagnose__col" data-v-68c73f99><p class="diagnose__description b1 js-fade" data-v-68c73f99> Rectogesic® ointment is a non-prescription treatment that has been clinically shown to provide rapid and sustained relief of pain associated with medically diagnosed anal fissures and the active ingredient (0.2% w/w glyceryl trinitrate) has been shown to promote wound healing in 2–8 weeks.<sup data-v-68c73f99>1-4</sup></p><p>Available in 15 g or 30 g</p><img src="<?php echo get_stylesheet_directory_uri(); ?>/images/main/ointment.png" alt="ointment" class="diagnose__image image-single js-fade" data-v-68c73f99></div></div><div class="diagnose__block" data-v-68c73f99><div class="diagnose__col" data-v-68c73f99><p class="diagnose__title h1 js-fade" data-v-68c73f99>How does it work?</p><p class="diagnose__description b1 js-fade" data-v-68c73f99> Rectogesic® contains the active ingredient glyceryl trinitrate.<sup data-v-68c73f99>1 </sup> It works by releasing a chemical called nitric oxide which relaxes the anal sphincter.<sup data-v-68c73f99>5</sup> This helps to relieve pain and promote wound healing.<sup data-v-68c73f99>2-8</sup></p></div><div class="diagnose__col" data-v-68c73f99><div class="images-compare js-fade" data-v-68c73f99><img src="<?php echo get_stylesheet_directory_uri(); ?>/images/main/no_fissure.png" alt="no fissure" width="600" height="511" data-v-68c73f99><img src="<?php echo get_stylesheet_directory_uri(); ?>/images/main/fissure.png" alt="fissure" width="600" height="511" data-v-68c73f99></div></div></div></div></section><section class="apply-section" data-v-5588cc5e><div class="how-apply" data-v-5588cc5e data-v-d63afe53><div class="how-apply__left" data-v-d63afe53><p class="how-apply__left-title h1 js-fade" data-v-d63afe53>How to apply Rectogesic®<sup data-v-d63afe53>9</sup></p><p class="how-apply__left-description b1 js-fade" data-v-d63afe53> Rectogesic® is an external ointment that can be self-applied by patients using the following steps:<sup data-v-d63afe53>*</sup></p><div class="how-apply__steps" data-v-d63afe53><!--[--><div class="apply-step js-fade" data-v-d63afe53><div class="apply-step" data-v-d63afe53 data-v-7940aca8><div class="num-wrap" data-v-7940aca8><div class="step-num" data-v-7940aca8>01</div><div class="line" data-v-7940aca8></div></div><p class="step-description p2" data-v-7940aca8>Wrap your finger in plastic wrap or use a finger cot available from your pharmacist</p></div></div><div class="apply-step js-fade" data-v-d63afe53><div class="apply-step" data-v-d63afe53 data-v-7940aca8><div class="num-wrap" data-v-7940aca8><div class="step-num" data-v-7940aca8>02</div><div class="line" data-v-7940aca8></div></div><p class="step-description p2" data-v-7940aca8>Place your finger alongside the 1.5 cm dosing line located on the side of the carton</p></div></div><div class="apply-step js-fade" data-v-d63afe53><div class="apply-step" data-v-d63afe53 data-v-7940aca8><div class="num-wrap" data-v-7940aca8><div class="step-num" data-v-7940aca8>03</div><div class="line" data-v-7940aca8></div></div><p class="step-description p2" data-v-7940aca8>Dispense Rectogesic® along your finger and use the line to measure the desired dose</p></div></div><div class="apply-step js-fade" data-v-d63afe53><div class="apply-step" data-v-d63afe53 data-v-7940aca8><div class="num-wrap" data-v-7940aca8><div class="step-num" data-v-7940aca8>04</div><div class="line" data-v-7940aca8></div></div><p class="step-description p2" data-v-7940aca8>Gently apply Rectogesic® into the anal canal to the depth of the first finger joint (approximately 1 cm)</p></div></div><div class="apply-step js-fade" data-v-d63afe53><div class="apply-step" data-v-d63afe53 data-v-7940aca8><div class="num-wrap" data-v-7940aca8><div class="step-num" data-v-7940aca8>05</div><div class="line" data-v-7940aca8></div></div><p class="step-description p2" data-v-7940aca8>Apply Rectogesic® up to three times daily as directed by your doctor <sup data-v-7940aca8="">*†</sup></p></div></div><div class="apply-step js-fade" data-v-d63afe53><div class="apply-step" data-v-d63afe53 data-v-7940aca8><div class="num-wrap" data-v-7940aca8><div class="step-num" data-v-7940aca8>06</div><!----></div><p class="step-description p2" data-v-7940aca8>Wash hands after use</p></div></div><!--]--></div><p class="how-apply__bottom-text b1" data-v-d63afe53> *Rectogesic® contains glyceryl trinitrate and must be used strictly as directed.<sup data-v-d63afe53>9</sup><br/><sup data-v-d63afe53>†</sup>To avoid the development of tolerance, ensure there is a 12-hour period each day where Rectogesic® is not used.<sup data-v-d63afe53>9</sup></p></div><div class="how-apply__right" data-v-d63afe53><div class="how-apply__right-illustration" data-v-d63afe53><img class="steps-image js-fade" src="<?php echo get_stylesheet_directory_uri(); ?>/images/main/instruction.svg" alt="steps" data-v-d63afe53><img class="ointment-image js-fade" src="<?php echo get_stylesheet_directory_uri(); ?>/images/main/ointment.png" alt="ointment" data-v-d63afe53><div class="request-btn js-fade" data-v-d63afe53><a href="/order-samples/" target="_self" class="button" data-v-d63afe53 data-v-8cc40661>Request free samples</a></div></div><p class="how-apply__right-bottom-text b1" data-v-d63afe53> Please refer to the instructions for use leaflet for more information.<sup data-v-d63afe53>9</sup></p></div></div></section><section class="precautions-section" data-v-5588cc5e><div class="precautions" data-v-5588cc5e data-v-b3e53eb4><div class="precautions-left" data-v-b3e53eb4><p class="h1 js-fade" data-v-b3e53eb4> Precautions and warnings<span class="b1" data-v-b3e53eb4><sup data-v-b3e53eb4>1 , 9</sup></span></p></div><div class="precautions-right b1" data-v-b3e53eb4><div class="" data-v-b3e53eb4><p class="js-fade" data-v-b3e53eb4> Rectogesic® may cause headaches. Do not use more than directed. You may experience a fainting effect or dizziness following application of Rectogesic®.<br data-v-b3e53eb4>Unless a doctor has told you to, do not use if you: </p><ul class="precautions-right__list" data-v-b3e53eb4><li class="js-fade" data-v-b3e53eb4> Suffer from severe anaemia, glaucoma, hypotension, or increased intracranial pressure </li><li class="js-fade" data-v-b3e53eb4> Take medications to treat erectile dysfunction or heart conditions </li></ul><p class="js-fade" data-v-b3e53eb4> Ask your doctor or pharmacist for advice if you are pregnant or breastfeeding. </p><p class="mt-18 js-fade" data-v-b3e53eb4> Notify your doctor or pharmacist if you are allergic to glyceryl trinitrate. Please refer to the instructions for use leaflet for more information. Consult your doctor if symptoms persist. Contains 3.8% w/w alcohol. </p><p class="bottom-text p5 js-fade" data-v-b3e53eb4> REFERENCES: 1. Rectogesic® product label. 2. Ahmada J, <i>et al</i>. <i>Int J Surg</i>. 2007;5(6):429–432. 3. Bailey HR, <i>et al</i>. <i>Dis Colon Rectum</i>. 2002;45(9):1192–9. 4. Lund JN, Scholefield JH. <i>Lancet</i>. 1997;349(9044):11–4. 5. Zaghiyan KN, Fleshner P. <i>Clin Colon Rectal Surg</i>. 2011;24(1):22–30. 6. Kennedy ML, <i>et al</i>. <i>Dis Colon Rectum</i>. 1999;42(8):1000-6. 7. Tan KY, <i>et al</i>. <i>Br J Surg</i>. 2006;93(12):1464–8. 8. Hwang DY, <i>et al</i>. <i>Dis Colon Rectum</i>. 2003;46(7):950–4. 9. Rectogesic® Consumer Medicine Information. </p></div></div></div></section></div><!----></div><!----><!--]--></div><script type="application/json" id="__NUXT_DATA__" data-ssr="true">[["Reactive",1],{"data":2,"state":3,"_errors":7,"serverRendered":8,"path":9,"prerenderedAt":10},{},{"$sisModalVisible":4,"$sisFooterNavigation":4,"$sactive-scene":5,"$scurrentSectionId":6},false,0,"interactive",{},true,"/",1690880870231]</script><script>window.__NUXT__={};window.__NUXT__.config={public:{},app:{baseURL:"/rectogesic-3d-model",buildAssetsDir:"/_nuxt/",cdnURL:""}}</script><script type="module" src="<?php echo get_stylesheet_directory_uri(); ?>/_nuxt/entry.22957f2a.js" crossorigin></script>



